6.4 Create a Notification
Lesson
Notifications in ServiceNow are automated email alerts that keep stakeholders informed about important events and changes in the platform. As a System Administrator, you'll frequently configure notifications to ensure the right people receive timely information about critical situations. Notifications consist of three key components: When to send (trigger conditions), Who receives it (users and groups), and What it contains (subject and message content). Understanding how to leverage field references and dynamic variables makes notifications both powerful and maintainable.

Scenario
The IT Product Owner for the Infinity (HHD) service has requested that specific stakeholders be notified whenever a critical (Priority 1) incident is created or updated for the Infinity (HHD) service offering. Your task is to create an email notification that will automatically alert the Training Service owner, the Infinity (HHD) service offering owner, and all members of the Training Technology Support group. The notification must include dynamic content that makes it easy for recipients to take immediate action.

Task Objectives
1. Create a new notification named "P1 Infinity (HHD) Incident" on the Incident table.

2. Configure when to send the notification:
- When P1 incidents are inserted or updated. Note: select "Insert" and "Update" checkboxes, in addition to "Send when | record inserted or updated"
- Conditions:
     - Active is true AND
     - Priority is 1-Critical AND
     - Service offering is Infinity (HHD)


3. Specify who will receive the notification:
- Users/Groups in fields: Service.Ownedby and Service offering.Owned by (dot-walking is required). Note: When dot-walking in this task, scroll up to the top of the "Available" list collector, and select "Incident fields" to restore the original parent fields.
- Groups: Training Technology Support

4. Specify what it will contain: 
- Subject: IMPORTANT! P1 Infinity (HHD) Incident ${number}
- Body: Critical Incident ${URI_REF} has been created for Infinity (HHD) service offering.

To begin, navigate to All > System Notification > Email > Notifications.
6.5 Test and verify Notification Settings
Lesson
Creating a notification is only half the battle—you must also test it to ensure it functions correctly. Testing notifications involves creating a record that meets the trigger conditions, then verifying the notification was generated and formatted properly. Since email may not be enabled in development instances, ServiceNow provides the Outbox in System Mailboxes where administrators can preview and verify all outbound notifications. This testing process is critical for quality assurance before deploying notifications to production environments.

Scenario
You've just created the "P1 Infinity (HHD) Incident" notification, and now you need to test it to ensure it triggers correctly. To do this, you'll impersonate Beth Anglin (a user in your instance) and create a Priority 1 incident for the Infinity (HHD) service offering that meets all the notification trigger conditions. Then, you'll verify that the notification was generated in the Outbox and review its content to confirm the dynamic variables rendered correctly and the proper recipients were identified.

Task Objectives
1. Impersonate Beth Anglin to create a test incident.

2. Create a Priority 1 incident that meets the notification trigger conditions:
- Caller: Buster Wubbel
- Service offering: Infinity (HHD)
- Impact: 1 - High
- Urgency: 1 - High
- Priority: 1 – Critical (auto-fills)
- Short description: Test of P1 Incident for Infinity HHD

3. End the impersonation and return to your System Administrator session

4. Navigate to the Outbox to locate the triggered notification.

5. Preview the email to verify formatting and dynamic content. Review notification details including the recipient list.

To begin, navigate to the User menu > Impersonate user. 



